Dr. Bashir Jamoh, the direc­tor general of Nigerian Mar­itime Administration and Safety Agency (NIMASA), has urged 22 member-coun­tries of the Abuja Memo­randum of Understanding on Port State Control (Abuja MoU) to improve on their fi­nancial contributions to the organisation Jamoh, who was repre­sented by Shehu Ahmed, NI­MASA’s Executive Director of Operations, identified that not more than ten countries fulfilling their financial obli­gations to Abuja MoU could be improved upon. Jamoh, who was speaking on Monday at a workshop for heads of maritime adminis­trations in Lagos, also reiter­ated NIMASA’s unflinching commitment to Abuja MoU in its focus for reduction of sub­standard ships, curbing ma­rine pollution and ensuring good working conditions of crew members onboard ships within member states waters. -Advertisement- He urged his fellow heads of maritime administrations to learn, compare notes and offer expertise to colleagues in 22 member-countries par­ticipating in the three day Lagos workshop which en­courages a minimum of 15 percent of foreign vessels for inspection.